Here's the xUnit equivalent. The key mappings are:

| NUnit | xUnit |
|-------|-------|
| `[SetUp]` | Constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp/TearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` + fixture's `Dispose` |

```csharp
// Shared fixture handles one-time setup/teardown
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    // Constructor replaces [SetUp]
    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture _)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    // IDisposable.Dispose replaces [TearDown]
    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- xUnit creates a **new class instance per test**, so the constructor/`Dispose` run for each test — matching `[SetUp]`/`[TearDown]` semantics.
- `IClassFixture<T>` ensures the fixture is created once and shared across all tests in the class, matching `[OneTimeSetUp]`/`[OneTimeTearDown]`.
- If setup/teardown need to be `async`, implement `IAsyncLifetime` (with `InitializeAsync`/`DisposeAsync`) instead.
